'''Michael Harwood''' (1934, Boston – 24 November 1989, San Diego) was a naturalist, environmentalist, and author.<ref name=Obit>{{cite web|author=Howe, Marvine|date=26 November 1989|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/11/26/obituaries/michael-harwood-55-naturalist.html|title=Michael Harwood, 55, Naturalist|publisher=NY Times}}</ref>

Harwood received his secondary education from [[The Putney School]] in Vermont and graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1956. He became the third husband of the author Mary B. Durant in 1966.<ref>{{cite book|title=Death in slow motion: a memoir of a daughter, her mother, and the beast called Alzheimer's|author=Cooney, Eleanor|publisher=Harper Collins|year=2004|postscript=; pbk|page=4|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Death_in_Slow_Motion.html?id=98QyhyBc4fAC&pg=PA4}}</ref>

He was a co-winner of the 1981 [[John Burroughs Medal]] for ''On the Road With John James Audubon'', which he co-authored with his wife Mary Durant. The book is organized as a travel journal which recounts how the two authors spent more than a year camping along the various North American itineraries recorded in Audubon's journals.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Review of ''On the Road with John James Audubon'' by Mary Durant and Michael Harwood|date=11 August 1980|newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|author=Hancock, Wade|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1980/0811/081119.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Fink, Louis|title=Review of ''On the Road with John James Audubon'' by Mary Durant and Michael Harwood|journal=The Chat|date=Spring 1981|volume=45|issue=2|pages=55–56|url=https://www.carolinabirdclub.org/chat/issues/1981/v45n2reviews.pdf}}</ref>

Harwood attended the 1974 foundational meeting<ref>{{cite web|title=HMANA History|website=HMANA|url=http://www.hmana.org/hmana-history/}}</ref> and was a president of the Hawk Migration Association of North America. He was a member of the board of the [[Hawk Mountain Sanctuary]] at [[Kempton, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Obit/>

